# Refine the SGAI spec (minor version refinement, vN.M → vN.M+1)

**Inputs**:
- The most recent `../output/v*-sgai-spec.md` (the spec to refine,
  NOT regenerate). The filename version may be a major (`vN`) or
  a minor (`vN.M`); the new minor version is computed by
  incrementing the rightmost component (see "Versioning" below).
- The matching `../output-analysis/v*-spec-validation.md` (gaps,
  ambiguities, edge cases — Step 7 sidecar).
- The matching `../output-analysis/v*-detail-review.md` (autofixes
  already applied + flagged items requiring semantic decisions —
  Step 7.5 log).
- The matching `../output-analysis/v*-dash-conformance-audit.md`
  (V / M / N verdicts per construct + remedy sequence — Step 8
  audit).
- `../context/` (read-only here; used only for grounding existing
  claims, NEVER for regeneration). The refinement does not consume
  new context — by definition requirements stay fixed across a
  minor refinement.

**Output**: `../output/v<N.M+1>-sgai-spec.md`. The refined spec,
delta-only against the input spec. Sections without any issue in
the analysis inputs MUST be carried over byte-identical.

**Skip if**: `../output/v<N.M+1>-sgai-spec.md` already exists AND
its mtime is newer than ALL of:
- the input spec `../output/v<N.M>-sgai-spec.md`,
- `../output-analysis/v<N.M>-spec-validation.md`,
- `../output-analysis/v<N.M>-detail-review.md`,
- `../output-analysis/v<N.M>-dash-conformance-audit.md`,
- this prompt (`prompts/4-auto-refine/refine-spec.prompt`).

**Execution mode**: fresh subagent context. The agent reads only
the spec, the three analysis sidecars, and `../context/` for
grounding. It MUST NOT query NotebookLM or any external authority —
grounding happened in the major build, and a minor refinement
operates strictly inside that grounding envelope.

---

## What this prompt is for

A minor refinement (vN.M+1) addresses issues surfaced by the
validation sidecar, the detail-review log, and the DASH conformance
audit, WITHOUT changing requirements and WITHOUT changing
architectural choices. It is delta-only: untouched sections of the
spec carry over byte-identical from the input.

Two iteration scales coexist in the project:

- **Major (vN+1)** — requirements changed, architecture changed,
  new constructs introduced, or a construct retired. Triggered by
  edits inside `../context/`. Built from scratch by
  `build-all.prompt` (which calls `build-spec.prompt`).
- **Minor (vN.M+1)** — requirements unchanged, only wording /
  internal consistency / cross-reference accuracy / DASH conformance
  remedies for issues documented in the analyses. Built by this
  prompt.

The intent is to converge a single major version through a few
small iterations before promoting to the next major, instead of
re-grounding the whole spec on every fix.

## Constraints on the refined spec output

- **No new requirements.** A minor refinement MUST NOT introduce
  new normative obligations, new actor responsibilities, new use
  cases, or new architectural choices. If an issue in the inputs
  requires any of those, do NOT apply it — record it under
  "Refinement gaps" (see below) and leave the rest of the spec
  alone.
- **Delta-only edits.** Sections of the spec that have NO issue in
  the validation sidecar, the detail-review log, or the conformance
  audit MUST be carried over byte-identical. The refinement is not
  a rewrite.
- **Same header, same edition.** The refined spec MUST start with
  the same `# SGAI for MPEG-DASH ...` title and the same edition /
  base-spec reference as the input. Only the version line at the
  top advances (`v<N.M>` → `v<N.M+1>`).
- **Traceable deltas.** Every applied edit MUST be annotated with
  an HTML comment `<!-- refine: <issue-id> -->` placed at the
  nearest line above the edited content. The `<issue-id>` is the
  identifier of the issue in the source analysis (e.g.
  `v4-detail-review.md#flag-3`, `v4-dash-conformance-audit.md#N1`,
  `v4-spec-validation.md#gap-2`). Markdown ignores HTML comments,
  so this does not affect rendering — but a downstream auditor can
  grep them to audit which changes came from which input.
- **No external grounding.** Do NOT call NotebookLM. Do NOT cite
  new external sources. If a remedy in the conformance audit
  references a DASH 6th rule, the audit already grounded that rule;
  this prompt only applies the remedy.
- **History preserved.** The input spec `v<N.M>-sgai-spec.md`
  MUST remain untouched. Never overwrite it.

## Versioning rule

Resolve the new version from the input spec filename:

| Input filename            | Output filename             |
|---------------------------|-----------------------------|
| `v3-sgai-spec.md`         | `v3.1-sgai-spec.md`         |
| `v3.1-sgai-spec.md`       | `v3.2-sgai-spec.md`         |
| `v3.7-sgai-spec.md`       | `v3.8-sgai-spec.md`         |
| `v4-sgai-spec.md`         | `v4.1-sgai-spec.md`         |
| `v4.1-sgai-spec.md`       | `v4.2-sgai-spec.md`         |

Rule: if the version has no minor component, append `.1`. If it
already has a minor component, increment that minor component by 1
and keep the major component unchanged.

The version label at the top of the spec body advances accordingly
(any inline reference such as "this is v4" must be updated to "this
is v4.1", etc.).

## Task

### 1. Locate inputs

Identify the most recent `../output/v*-sgai-spec.md` (call its
version `v<N.M>`; the major case is `M=∅`, treat as `M=0` for the
arithmetic above). Identify the three matching analysis sidecars in
`../output-analysis/` using the same `v<N.M>` prefix.

If any of the three sidecars is missing, abort with a message:

```
ABORT: refine-spec requires all three sidecars for v<N.M>:
  - spec-validation.md
  - detail-review.md
  - dash-conformance-audit.md
Run the corresponding prompts first.
```

### 2. Collect the issue list

Read the three sidecars end to end and collect every issue that
proposes a change to the spec:

- From `v<N.M>-spec-validation.md`:
  - **Gaps**: only address those NOT already routed into §5.a,
    §5.b or §5.c by the validator. Each gap in §1 of the sidecar
    must carry a `See Actionable TODO Tk`, `See Flagged f-k`, or
    `See Deferred d-k` back-reference; if no back-reference is
    present, the validator left it unrouted — treat as Flagged
    (apply the §5.d tie-breaker). Historic behaviour for unrouted
    gaps: most are requirement-level → record as Refinement gaps
    (see step 4) UNLESS the spec already states the rule
    elsewhere and just needs the cross-reference made explicit.
  - **Edge cases**: only address those NOT already routed into
    §5.a, §5.b or §5.c by the validator. Each edge case in §2 of
    the sidecar must carry a `See Actionable TODO Tk`, `See
    Flagged f-k`, or `See Deferred d-k` back-reference; if no
    back-reference is present, the validator left it unrouted —
    treat as Flagged (apply the §5.d tie-breaker). Historic
    behaviour for unrouted edge cases: if handling requires a new
    construct, defer to Refinement gaps; if it requires only
    tightening an existing sentence, apply.
  - **Ambiguities**: only address those NOT already routed into
    §5.a, §5.b or §5.c by the validator. Each ambiguity in §3 of
    the sidecar must carry a `See Actionable TODO Tk`, `See
    Flagged f-k`, or `See Deferred d-k` back-reference; if no
    back-reference is present, the validator left it unrouted —
    treat as Flagged (apply the §5.d tie-breaker).

- From `v<N.M>-spec-validation.md` §5 (Disposition of findings):
  - **§5.a Actionable TODOs**: MUST apply every row, in table
    order. Each row carries a concrete edit description and a
    finding-ref (`A-2`, `G-3`, etc.). For each TODO Tk: locate
    the spec section, apply the edit, annotate with
    `<!-- refine: v<N.M>-spec-validation.md#T<k> -->`. No
    triage, no judgement — if the validator emitted it as a
    TODO, the refine agent executes it. If applying a TODO is
    mechanically impossible (the spec section it points to no
    longer exists after a previous refine pass), record it in
    Refinement gaps with the reason "TODO target missing" and
    move on.
  - **§5.b Flagged for review**: MUST NOT touch. These belong to
    the human review pass. Carrying them forward to Refinement
    gaps is OK; editing the spec around them is NOT.
  - **§5.c Deferred to context/**: MUST NOT touch (same as
    today's "Refinement gaps" outcome). Carry forward in the
    trailing table.
  - **Conflict resolution**: if a row in §5.a points at the
    same spec section as a flag from `v<N.M>-detail-review.md`
    with a different remedy, **§5.a takes precedence** —
    validation is the strategic pass; detail-review is tactical.

- From `v<N.M>-detail-review.md`:
  - **Autofixes** are already applied to the spec by Step 7.5 —
    skip them.
  - **Flagged issues** are the deltas this prompt OWNS. Apply each
    one using the suggested resolution from the log; if the log
    recommends "rename X to Y", do the rename consistently across
    the whole spec.

- From `v<N.M>-dash-conformance-audit.md`:
  - **Non-conforming (N)** items: apply the suggested fix.
  - **Marginal (M)** items: apply the clarification the audit
    proposes (typically a tightening sentence, a unit suffix, or
    an explicit cross-reference).
  - **Conforming (V)** items: nothing to do.
  - If the audit has a final "remedy sequence", treat it as the
    canonical ordered list of edits — apply in that order.

### 3. Apply edits

For each collected issue:

1. Locate the section / line in the input spec.
2. Determine the minimal change. If multiple changes would satisfy
   the issue, choose the one closest to the surrounding wording.
3. Apply the change in the output spec.
4. Annotate with `<!-- refine: <issue-id> -->` on the line above
   the edit. The `<issue-id>` references the analysis file and a
   stable handle: e.g. `v4-detail-review.md#flag-3`,
   `v4-dash-conformance-audit.md#N1`, `v4-spec-validation.md#amb-7`.
5. If the change requires updating multiple places (e.g. renaming
   an attribute affects chapter 5, the annex examples, and the
   syntax tables), apply consistently across all sites. Annotate
   each site.

### 4. Refinement gaps section

If an issue cannot be resolved by a minimal change because it
requires a new requirement, a new construct, or an architectural
decision, do NOT apply it. Instead, append a section at the very
end of the refined spec (after the last annex):

```markdown
## Refinement gaps

The following items from the v<N.M> analyses could not be resolved
within a minor refinement (they require requirement-level changes
or architectural decisions). They are carried forward for the next
major build to address.

| # | Source | Issue ID | Summary | Why minor refinement is insufficient |
|---|--------|----------|---------|--------------------------------------|
| 1 | validation | gap-2 | `<one-line summary>` | `<one-line why>` |
| ... | ... | ... | ... | ... |
```

If there are no such items, omit the section entirely.

### 5. Write the output

Write the refined spec to `../output/v<N.M+1>-sgai-spec.md`. Do
NOT overwrite the input spec. Carry over byte-identical the
sections that had no issues. Apply the deltas with their inline
`<!-- refine: ... -->` annotations. Append the Refinement gaps
section if any.

## Reporting (stdout)

After writing the output spec, emit a single summary line to stdout
so the orchestrator (or the operator) can audit the run:

```
wrote ../output/v<N.M+1>-sgai-spec.md, <NN> lines, <X> deltas applied, <Y> deltas deferred (Refinement gaps), <Z> sections unchanged
```

Where:
- `<NN>` — line count of the refined spec.
- `<X>` — count of `<!-- refine: ... -->` annotations applied.
- `<Y>` — count of rows in the Refinement gaps table (0 if section
  omitted).
- `<Z>` — count of top-level sections in the spec that the refine
  did not modify (rough estimate is fine — count by `^##`).

## What this prompt explicitly does NOT do

- Does NOT re-run NotebookLM or query any external source.
- Does NOT regenerate sections without issues in the analyses.
- Does NOT introduce new requirements, design principles,
  constructs, namespaces, or actor responsibilities.
- Does NOT modify anything in `../context/`,
  `../context-analysis/`, `../prompts/`, the input spec
  `../output/v<N.M>-sgai-spec.md`, or the three input sidecars in
  `../output-analysis/`.
- Does NOT collapse build history — every prior `v*-sgai-spec.md`
  stays on disk.

## Tone

Match the input spec verbatim: same RFC 2119 vocabulary, same
attribute table pattern, same tone. The refinement is invisible at
the prose level — only the surgical deltas carry new bytes.
